05506nam a22008895i 9780231525459DE-B159720190708092533.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||190708s2011    nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802315254597 a10.7312/hung152022doi  a(DE-B1597)458957  a(OCoLC)741453655  a(OCoLC)979754079  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aHN733b.H86 2015 7aHIS0080002bisacsh04a303.484095109033223  aNO 85002rvk1 aHung, Ho-fung, eauthor.10aProtest with Chinese Characteristics :bDemonstrations, Riots, and Petitions in the Mid-Qing Dynasty /cHo-fung Hung. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2011] 4cÂ©2011  a1 online resource :b25 illus. 11 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tFIGURES -- tTABLES -- tPREFACE -- tINTRODUCTION -- t1. Market Expansion, State Centralization, and Neo-Confucianism in Qing China -- t2. Documenting the Three Waves of Mid-Qing Protest -- t3. Filial-Loyal Demonstrations, 1740-1759 -- t4. Riots Into Rebellion, 1776-1795 -- t5. Resistance and Petitions, 1820-1839 -- t6. Mid-Qing Protests in Comparative Perspective -- tEpilogue: The Past in the Present -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tGlossary -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe origin of political modernity has long been tied to the Western history of protest and revolution, the currents of which many believe sparked popular dissent worldwide. Reviewing nearly one thousand instances of protest in China from the eighteenth to the early-nineteenth centuries, Ho-fung Hung charts an evolution of Chinese dissent that stands apart from Western trends. Hung samples from mid-Qing petitions and humble plaints to the emperor. He revisits rallies, riots, market strikes, and other forms of contention rarely considered in previous studies. Drawing on new world history, which accommodates parallels and divergences between political-economic and cultural developments East and West, Hung shows how the centralization of political power and an expanding market, coupled with a persistent Confucianist orthodoxy, shaped protesters' strategies and appeals in Qing China. This unique form of mid-Qing protest combined a quest for justice and autonomy with a filial-loyal respect for the imperial center, and Hung's careful research ties this distinct characteristic to popular protest in China today. As Hung makes clear, the nature of these protests prove late imperial China was anything but a stagnant and tranquil empire before the West cracked it open. In fact, the origins of modern popular politics in China predate the 1911 Revolution. Hung's work ultimately establishes a framework others can use to compare popular protest among different cultural fabrics. His book fundamentally recasts the evolution of such acts worldwide.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 08. Jul 2019) 0aDemonstrationszChinaxHistoryy18th century. 0aPetitionszChinaxHistoryy18th century. 0aProtest movementszChinaxHistoryy18th century. 0aRiotszChinaxHistoryy18th century. 70(DE-601)1041626510(DE-588)4003554-2aAufstand2gnd 70(DE-601)1044643050(DE-588)4226404-2aProtestbewegung2gnd 70(DE-601)1056507650(DE-588)4137338-8aPetition2gnd 70(DE-601)1061006610(DE-588)4070285-6aDemonstration2gnd 7aHISTORY / Asia / China.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagez978311064977208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP eBook Package 2000-2015z978311066254208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044247208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP eBook Package Backlist 2000-2014z978311045952440uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/